<subSubSection pageId="31" pageNumber="32" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="31.[189,334,889,915]" box="[189,334,889,915]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,334,889,915]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,334,889,915]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Description</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="31.[189,1398,940,1046]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">
HABITUS. Encrusting sponge 
<quantity box="[537,608,940,967]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" unit="mm" value="5.0">5 mm</quantity>
thick and 
<quantity box="[740,816,941,967]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" unit="cm" value="10.0">10 cm</quantity>
long (
<figureCitation box="[897,1010,940,967]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="32.[189,232,1918,1944]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,265,1878]" captionTargetId="figure@32.[189,1398,265,1878]" captionTargetPageId="32" captionText="Fig. 13. Scopalina cribrosa Bertolino, Costa &amp; Pansini sp. nov., holotype (CILE 32; MSGN 61498). A. The holotype in life. B. Styles. C. Magnification of the style ends." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4022427" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4022427/files/figure.png" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Fig. 13A</figureCitation>
). Surface slightly conulose with visible oscula, ostia and canal network. Slightly hispid. Colour in life reddish orange (
<figureCitation box="[1270,1385,980,1007]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="32.[189,232,1918,1944]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,265,1878]" captionTargetId="figure@32.[189,1398,265,1878]" captionTargetPageId="32" captionText="Fig. 13. Scopalina cribrosa Bertolino, Costa &amp; Pansini sp. nov., holotype (CILE 32; MSGN 61498). A. The holotype in life. B. Styles. C. Magnification of the style ends." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4022427" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4022427/files/figure.png" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Fig. 13A</figureCitation>
). Consistency soft.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="31.[189,1399,1090,1157]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">SKELETON. Choanosomal skeleton consisting of bundles of thin styles entirely enclosed in spongin. Dendritic fibres rising up from basal spongin plate. Low spicular density.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="31.[189,1398,1200,1267]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">
SPICULES. Megascleres: Smooth styles, bent near the head, ending with tip not pointed but almost rounded (
<figureCitation box="[301,384,1240,1266]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="32.[189,232,1918,1944]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,265,1878]" captionTargetId="figure@32.[189,1398,265,1878]" captionTargetPageId="32" captionText="Fig. 13. Scopalina cribrosa Bertolino, Costa &amp; Pansini sp. nov., holotype (CILE 32; MSGN 61498). A. The holotype in life. B. Styles. C. Magnification of the style ends." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4022427" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4022427/files/figure.png" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Fig. 13</figureCitation>
B–C), 520–(1616.15)–2091 μm long and 2.5–(23.25)–32.5 μm thick.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="31.[189,285,1310,1336]" box="[189,285,1310,1336]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,285,1310,1336]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,285,1310,1336]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Habitat</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="31.[189,1093,1361,1388]" box="[189,1093,1361,1388]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">
Species lives at a depth of 
<quantity box="[502,563,1362,1388]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" unit="m" value="20.0">20 m</quantity>
, on a rocky slope covered by coralline algae.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="31" pageNumber="32" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="31.[189,303,1432,1458]" box="[189,303,1432,1458]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,303,1432,1458]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,303,1432,1458]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Remarks</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="31.[189,1399,1483,2027]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">
From five species of the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schmidt" authorityYear="1862" box="[478,595,1483,1509]" class="Demospongiae" family="Scopalinidae" genus="Scopalina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Halichondrida" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[478,595,1483,1509]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Scopalina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
genus known in the Southern Hemisphere (
<tableCitation box="[1109,1200,1483,1509]" captionStart="Table 7" captionStartId="33.[188,257,542,571]" captionText="Table 7 (continued on the next page). Morphological characters and distribution of the species of Scopalina Schmidt, 1862. The distribution refers to that present in the World Porifera Database (van Soest et al. 2020)." pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Table 7</tableCitation>
), only 
<taxonomicName authority="Goodwin, Jones, Neely &amp; Brickle, 2011" authorityName="Goodwin, Jones, Neely &amp; Brickle" authorityYear="2011" class="Demospongiae" family="Scopalinidae" genus="Scopalina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Halichondrida" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="bunkeri">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Scopalina bunkeri</emphasis>
Goodwin, Jones, Neely &amp; Brickle, 2011
</taxonomicName>
has been recorded from Chilean coast by 
<bibRefCitation author="Bertolino" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Bertolino" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" pagination="306 - 320" refId="ref15474" refString="Bertolino M., Costa G., Reboa A., Bavestrello G., Pansini M., Betti F., Marzia Bo. &amp; Daneri G. 2019. The sponge fauna of the Seno Magdalena and Puyuhuapi Fjord (Chile), with a description of two new species. Zootaxa 4623 (2): 306 - 320. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4623.2.5" type="journal article" year="2019">
Bertolino 
<emphasis box="[189,247,1562,1588]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">et al.</emphasis>
(2019)
</bibRefCitation>
. The new species differs from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Goodwin, Jones, Neely &amp; Brickle" authorityYear="2011" box="[689,807,1562,1589]" class="Demospongiae" family="Scopalinidae" genus="Scopalina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Halichondrida" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="bunkeri">
<emphasis box="[689,807,1562,1589]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">S. bunkeri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having a very spiky surface and by the presence of smaller styles (
<tableCitation box="[406,500,1602,1629]" captionStart="Table 7" captionStartId="33.[188,257,542,571]" captionText="Table 7 (continued on the next page). Morphological characters and distribution of the species of Scopalina Schmidt, 1862. The distribution refers to that present in the World Porifera Database (van Soest et al. 2020)." pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Table 7</tableCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName authority="Bertolino &amp; Costa &amp; Bavestrello &amp; Pansini &amp; Daneri, 2020" authorityName="Bertolino &amp; Costa &amp; Bavestrello &amp; Pansini &amp; Daneri" authorityYear="2020" box="[526,752,1602,1628]" class="Demospongiae" family="Scopalinidae" genus="Scopalina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Halichondrida" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="cribrosa" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[526,752,1602,1628]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Scopalina cribrosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[762,856,1603,1629]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
differs from 
<taxonomicName authority="(Pulitzer-Finali, 1982)" baseAuthorityName="Pulitzer-Finali" baseAuthorityYear="1982" class="Demospongiae" family="Axinellidae" genus="Axinella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Halichondrida" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="australiensis">
<emphasis box="[1019,1202,1602,1629]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">S. australiensis</emphasis>
(Pulitzer-Finali, 1982)
</taxonomicName>
from Eastern 
<collectingCountry box="[425,533,1642,1668]" name="Australia" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Australia</collectingCountry>
in its external morphology, having an erect habit, large body and spicule size, but much smaller styles (
<tableCitation box="[537,627,1682,1709]" captionStart="Table 7" captionStartId="33.[188,257,542,571]" captionText="Table 7 (continued on the next page). Morphological characters and distribution of the species of Scopalina Schmidt, 1862. The distribution refers to that present in the World Porifera Database (van Soest et al. 2020)." pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Table 7</tableCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName authority="Bertolino &amp; Costa &amp; Bavestrello &amp; Pansini &amp; Daneri, 2020" authorityName="Bertolino &amp; Costa &amp; Bavestrello &amp; Pansini &amp; Daneri" authorityYear="2020" box="[648,870,1682,1708]" class="Demospongiae" family="Scopalinidae" genus="Scopalina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Halichondrida" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="cribrosa" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[648,870,1682,1708]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Scopalina cribrosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[877,967,1683,1709]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
differs from 
<taxonomicName authority="Goodwin, Jones, Neely &amp; Brickle, 2011" authorityName="Goodwin, Jones, Neely &amp; Brickle" authorityYear="2011" class="Demospongiae" family="Scopalinidae" genus="Scopalina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Halichondrida" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="erubescens">
<emphasis box="[1117,1275,1682,1708]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">S. erubescens</emphasis>
Goodwin, Jones, Neely &amp; Brickle, 2011
</taxonomicName>
from the Falklands / 
<collectingCountry box="[784,893,1722,1748]" name="Falkland Islands" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Malvinas</collectingCountry>
in its pale pink colour, a conulose surface, and styles that are four times shorter than those of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Goodwin, Jones, Neely &amp; Brickle" authorityYear="2011" box="[787,947,1762,1788]" class="Demospongiae" family="Scopalinidae" genus="Scopalina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Halichondrida" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="erubescens">
<emphasis box="[787,947,1762,1788]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">S. erubescens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<tableCitation box="[962,1054,1762,1788]" captionStart="Table 7" captionStartId="33.[188,257,542,571]" captionText="Table 7 (continued on the next page). Morphological characters and distribution of the species of Scopalina Schmidt, 1862. The distribution refers to that present in the World Porifera Database (van Soest et al. 2020)." pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Table 7</tableCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName authority="Bertolino &amp; Costa &amp; Bavestrello &amp; Pansini &amp; Daneri, 2020" authorityName="Bertolino &amp; Costa &amp; Bavestrello &amp; Pansini &amp; Daneri" authorityYear="2020" box="[1077,1300,1762,1788]" class="Demospongiae" family="Scopalinidae" genus="Scopalina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Halichondrida" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="cribrosa" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1077,1300,1762,1788]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Scopalina cribrosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1308,1399,1762,1788]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
differs from 
<taxonomicName authority="(Hooper, Cook, Hobbs &amp; Kennedy, 1997)" baseAuthorityName="Hooper, Cook, Hobbs &amp; Kennedy" baseAuthorityYear="1997" box="[343,984,1801,1828]" class="Demospongiae" family="Scopalinidae" genus="Scopalina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Halichondrida" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="hapalia">
<emphasis box="[343,465,1801,1828]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">S. hapalia</emphasis>
(Hooper, Cook, Hobbs &amp; Kennedy, 1997)
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[1062,1170,1801,1827]" name="Australia" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Australia</collectingCountry>
both in the colour and the presence of strongyles, which are lacking in the new species. Finally, regarding species of the Southern Hemisphere, 
<taxonomicName authority="Bertolino &amp; Costa &amp; Bavestrello &amp; Pansini &amp; Daneri, 2020" authorityName="Bertolino &amp; Costa &amp; Bavestrello &amp; Pansini &amp; Daneri" authorityYear="2020" box="[458,585,1881,1908]" class="Demospongiae" family="Scopalinidae" genus="Scopalina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Halichondrida" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="cribrosa" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[458,585,1881,1908]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">S. cribrosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[593,683,1882,1908]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
differs from 
<taxonomicName authority="(Lendenfeld, 1887)" baseAuthorityName="Lendenfeld" baseAuthorityYear="1887" box="[836,1221,1881,1908]" class="Demospongiae" family="Scopalinidae" genus="Scopalina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Halichondrida" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="incrustans">
<emphasis box="[836,987,1882,1908]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">S. incrustans</emphasis>
(Lendenfeld, 1887)
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[1291,1399,1881,1907]" name="Australia" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Australia</collectingCountry>
by its larger styles. The nine species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schmidt" authorityYear="1862" box="[662,779,1921,1947]" class="Demospongiae" family="Scopalinidae" genus="Scopalina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Halichondrida" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[662,779,1921,1947]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Scopalina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
reported from the Northern Hemisphere differ from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bertolino &amp; Costa &amp; Bavestrello &amp; Pansini &amp; Daneri" authorityYear="2020" box="[189,314,1961,1987]" class="Demospongiae" family="Scopalinidae" genus="Scopalina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Halichondrida" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="cribrosa">
<emphasis box="[189,314,1961,1987]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">S. cribrosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the size of spicules, and often in their shape (
<tableCitation box="[856,945,1961,1988]" captionStart="Table 7" captionStartId="33.[188,257,542,571]" captionText="Table 7 (continued on the next page). Morphological characters and distribution of the species of Scopalina Schmidt, 1862. The distribution refers to that present in the World Porifera Database (van Soest et al. 2020)." pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Table 7</tableCitation>
). We, therefore, propose that 
<taxonomicName authority="Bertolino &amp; Costa &amp; Bavestrello &amp; Pansini &amp; Daneri, 2020" authorityName="Bertolino &amp; Costa &amp; Bavestrello &amp; Pansini &amp; Daneri" authorityYear="2020" class="Demospongiae" family="Scopalinidae" genus="Scopalina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Halichondrida" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="cribrosa" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Scopalina cribrosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[295,385,2001,2027]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
should be considered as a species new to science.
</paragraph>
